title: Get support if you've been in care

$values.value: Starting life as an adult can be challenging, but you're not on your own.
If you have been in care or have come to the UK on your own, you can get support.

target.title: Who is this this support for?

$values.description: Who is this support for - left hand content block

$values.value: Who is this support for?
You may have the right to support if you are between 15 and 25 and:
have been in care
(for example, in foster care, residential care or supported lodgings)
have been in custody
(for example, in a secure children's home, secure training centre or young offender institution)
came the UK on your own
(to seek asylum).

When you leave care, you could get support with housing costs and finding somewhere to live.
Support you may have the right to
When you leave care, your local council may have a duty to help you find somewhere safe and suitable to live (suitable accommodation).
If you leave care at 16 or 17, your council must pay for your housing costs, like rent, bills and other expenses.
